127
00:12:24,350 --> 00:12:36,038
I've also done some, I've done several, well, 12 hours of observations of recess there, and also been talking to many teachers and parents across the district about recess over the past couple of years.

128
00:12:36,058 --> 00:12:39,700
I have a third grader at the Roberts, and I'll have an incoming kindergartner next year.

129
00:12:42,502 --> 00:12:43,162
I would say that,

130
00:12:44,585 --> 00:13:01,698
I know that in principle, the district believes in recess, but in my observations, there are many staff who do see the value in child-directed play, but also many others who are very upset by the normal ways that children play, and thus overly restrict the activities of the children.

131
00:13:02,639 --> 00:13:06,682
The concerns of the teachers and other staff do not bear out in the injury data.

132
00:13:08,943 --> 00:13:13,587
And in addition, indoor recess quality varies greatly across buildings and by teacher.

133
00:13:15,865 --> 00:13:28,530
Some teachers are really great at having actual playful activities inside, and others consistently put on a screen, which is not child-directed play, has nothing to do with development of agency or social skills.

134
00:13:28,710 --> 00:13:33,793
And I think that I would recommend that the district adopt a policy of no screen times during recess.

135
00:13:33,813 --> 00:13:36,894
Like there, yes, sometimes your class earns a movie,

136
00:13:37,347 --> 00:13:41,109
And so you do that, but it should not be allowed during indoor recess.

137
00:13:41,169 --> 00:13:48,233
And we need a better policy and structure training, I'm not sure what it is, ideas presented to staff for indoor recess.

138
00:13:49,393 --> 00:13:54,676
And I just want to maybe see if we can get a definition of child-directed play.

139
00:13:56,777 --> 00:14:02,740
The field of play work, which is a distinct professional approach to working with children,

140
00:14:03,975 --> 00:14:15,350
In playful settings, is that child directed play, which sometimes gets called free play or unstructured play is freely chosen personally directed and intrinsically motivated.

141
00:14:17,266 --> 00:14:25,289
This is the only time of the day, sometimes at all, for some kids who are in care all day or who are in other adult-directed activities all day.

142
00:14:25,629 --> 00:14:27,330
It's the only time that belongs to them.

143
00:14:27,390 --> 00:14:29,671
And this is the development of agency for human beings.

144
00:14:29,731 --> 00:14:45,617
So we really need to value it and make sure that activities at recess are encouraging that personally directed, intrinsically motivated, and personally directed things that children want to do.

145
00:14:46,597 --> 00:14:46,857
Thank you.

146
00:14:48,958 --> 00:14:50,139
Thank you very much.

147
00:14:50,519 --> 00:14:59,143
I appreciate the definition because I certainly said free play and had a rather vague conception of what that meant.

148
00:14:59,743 --> 00:15:06,986
Yeah, so free play is tricky because it connotes like monetary value or adults get really worried about chaos, right?

149
00:15:08,627 --> 00:15:15,950
And if, I mean, all of us are people who have worked with children and unstructured play is a misnomer there because I'm sure, I mean, if we think about even

150
00:15:16,933 --> 00:15:23,176
Calvin Ball is a really great illustration of how children structure their own play.

151
00:15:23,656 --> 00:15:26,858
But we've all been playing with a kid and bumped up against a rule that they make.

152
00:15:26,938 --> 00:15:31,280
So unstructured play is actually like a value statement on who's doing the structuring.

153
00:15:31,621 --> 00:15:35,202
The children are doing the structuring in their own child-directed play.

154
00:15:37,824 --> 00:15:38,184
Thank you.

155
00:15:38,204 --> 00:15:39,024
That's very helpful.

