622
01:08:20,257 --> 01:08:22,899
Who gets to decide what the kid needs?

623
01:08:22,919 --> 01:08:27,962
Because it feels like if it's not the kid, then it's the opposite of child-directed.

624
01:08:29,804 --> 01:08:36,188
And I mean, if a child is during recess not able to play with

625
01:08:36,936 --> 01:08:41,219
other kids in a way that is working, however that is defined.

626
01:08:42,720 --> 01:08:50,746
And, you know, the natural responses of the other kids is not doing the educating that frankly probably happens a lot of the time.

627
01:08:50,766 --> 01:09:01,093
You know, I can see how the adults coming in to try and like help things get better if that's necessary, makes sense.

628
01:09:01,173 --> 01:09:04,856
But wind blocks, I guess it feels a bit like,

629
01:09:07,407 --> 01:09:08,547
Who gets to decide that?

630
01:09:08,727 --> 01:09:11,748
I mean, are kids really going like, I'm not gonna do recess today.

631
01:09:11,828 --> 01:09:21,451
I'm gonna go and do something that's not considered recess because an adult thought you needed more support in some other way.

632
01:09:21,471 --> 01:09:31,213
I don't really follow how it, my understanding of wind block is very much that the adults are saying, you know, my kid isn't getting this math concept and it's the wind block.

633
01:09:31,253 --> 01:09:33,454
So we're gonna go over the math concept during wind block.

634
01:09:33,883 --> 01:09:45,529
Right, so my comment, though, in regards to the wind block was more the fact that the students are given opportunities to choose what they're interested in in recess time that they have the fields.

635
01:09:45,589 --> 01:09:46,469
They have the playground.

636
01:09:46,549 --> 01:09:47,750
They have the bucket of supplies.

637
01:09:47,810 --> 01:09:48,450
They have the chalk.

638
01:09:49,075 --> 01:09:50,497
can bring their library books out.

639
01:09:50,978 --> 01:09:53,541
There are opportunities for them to make the choices.

640
01:09:54,022 --> 01:10:02,392
My point is that there are some students that struggle with making that decision, and we have our professionals or staff that say to them, here's some opportunities that we have.

641
01:10:02,432 --> 01:10:03,674
What do you feel like playing today?

642
01:10:03,714 --> 01:10:05,236
Do you want to go and talk to so-and-so?

643
01:10:05,656 --> 01:10:14,624
They sort of guide it, but then there are options out there for them readily available was my analysis towards the wind block.

644
01:10:14,764 --> 01:10:27,395
It's not highly structured, but I wanted to make the point that it doesn't look the same for every student at recess because some kids are looking to get to that field as soon as they can because they can't wait to start the soccer game when others can't.

645
01:10:27,956 --> 01:10:32,300
That is so overwhelming to them that they want the chalk at the loop, and that's okay too.

646
01:10:33,201 --> 01:10:38,985
We don't want people to feel like they have to be, because your class is going out, this is what you have to play.

647
01:10:39,426 --> 01:10:40,446
That was more the analysis.

648
01:10:42,028 --> 01:10:42,368
Thank you.

649
01:10:42,408 --> 01:10:48,413
That makes much more sense.

650
01:10:49,074 --> 01:10:50,955
I guess it's about choice, not type of play.

651
01:10:50,975 --> 01:10:53,697
And this is something that grownups get mixed up all the time.

652
01:10:53,757 --> 01:11:00,903
And I think that the way we design play environments, this is coming up a lot with the McGlynn, is that playgrounds are designed for two types of play.

653
01:11:02,369 --> 01:11:05,751
You know, as a play worker, we identify like 16 types of play.

654
01:11:06,232 --> 01:11:12,276
So, play can be reading in the library, because it's about choice and agency and how you're spending that time.

655
01:11:12,296 --> 01:11:19,101
So, there are just many different types of play, and grownups tend to only be like, they need to be running around.

656
01:11:19,501 --> 01:11:25,225
But some kids need just that time to sit under the structure and hang out with a friend and chat, and that's okay, too.

657
01:11:25,586 --> 01:11:26,566
Kids can be quiet.

658
01:11:26,586 --> 01:11:27,587
It can still be play.

659
01:11:29,395 --> 01:11:36,701
I think, Paul, your comment about kids needing support at recess is really important to think about, is what does a child need to be able to access recess?

660
01:11:37,201 --> 01:11:42,265
And that could be its own whole separate discussion other than this policy access piece.

661
01:11:44,286 --> 01:11:44,747
Thank you.

